DPRK Foreign Ministry spokesman on S. Korea-Japan "fisheries accord"  
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 29 (KCNA) -- The spokesman for the Foreign Ministry of the DPRK described a new "fisheries accord" between South Korea and Japan as a criminal document of aggression and treachery and declared the "accord" null and void.
   He made clear this position in a statement issued today after Japan and the South Korean authorities exchanged "instruments of ratification" of the new "accord" on January 22 to carry it into effect.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Both in view of content and in view of character, the new "fisheries accord" is a criminal document of aggression and treachery, which gravely encroaches upon the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Korean nation, he said, and continued:   The "accord" completely ignores Korea's claim to the sovereignty over Tok Islet, part of its territory. It mirrors unilateral interests of Japan in terms of the definition of the waters of jurisdiction.
   The Japanese authorities goaded their South Korean counterparts with neither independence nor principle into signing the shameless "accord" of aggression in broad daylight. That fully shows that they are making desperate efforts to realise their wild ambition to stage a comeback to Korea as never before.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The dastardly treachery of the South Korean authorities who do not hesitate to sell off the interests of the nation in a bid to maintain their power and the criminal act of the Japanese authorities who are stretching their crooked tentacles of aggression to Korea give rise to the unanimous indignation from the Korean people. The treachery and criminal act can never be pardoned in any case.
   We never admit the recent "accord"which was announced by  a herd of traitors in South Korea who are not entitled to represent all the Korean people rigged up in conspiracy with Japan obsessed by the wild ambition for staging a comeback.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   We solemnly declare the "accord" null and void.
   The aggressors and traitors have gravely encroached upon the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Korean nation by carrying into effect the "fisheries accord" at a time when the situation which can be seen only on the eve of a war is prevailing in the Korean peninsula as a result of reckless military provocation on the part of the U.S., Japan and the South Korean authorities.
   They will certainly face a stern judgement.

S. Korean ruler's crimes cartooned 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, January 29 (KCNA) -- Press media of South Korea bitterly condemned the present ruler for his treachery and despicable scramble for power, cartooning the ugly sight of his floundering in political and economic crisis.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Magazine Hangyore 21 carried a caricature titled "aim of dispute over possession rights in Tok Islet." In the caricature the Japanese Prime Minister, after the signing of the criminal "South Korea-Japan fisheries accord", utters yells of delight before his clans, with a rich dish of fish in his hand, on which letters "more than  a half of the golden fishing ground" are seen. 
   A cartoon titled "politics and people's livelihood" of another magazine news people shows the present reality of South Korea where people's life has been driven into the depth of misery by corrupt politics. In the cartoon fat ruling and opposition political charlatans portrayed as frogs are steeped only in scramble for power, on the top of mountain in front of a closed building indicative of the death of "people's life" under the "trusteeship" in autumn.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Newspaper Hankuk Ilbo carried a cartoon entitled "no reaction" indicating failure of "restructuring" proposed by the chief executive of South Korea. In this cartoon the ruler "enforces" the five conglomerates to reduce their "weight" (business). However, they show no "reaction" but their weight increases, making the beam of a steelyard bent.
   Besides, caricatures on corruptness of the South Korean society were carried by the Newspaper Dong-A Ilbo, magazines news maker and weekly South Korea and other publications.
